editorialSummary.text: Big portions of typical diner fare served around the clock power this night-owl mainstay.

originalText.text: Quite a spacious diner with lots of seating either at the counter, in the booths or in a sort of conservatory part with big windows that look onto 8th. All the usual diner food and drink on offer plus some specials. Service is good and friendly too. Only downside if you're a foreigner is the usual US food mantra of quantity over quality - huge plates of food that are impossible to finish unless you're clinically obese so get wasted.

originalText.text:
Look, it's a 24 hour diner which does the biggest portions known to man even by US standards. HOWEVER, the service is fantastic - everyone was super friendly and lovely, and chatty. We had so much fun there. The chicken parmgiana sandwich was pretty good as was the Matzo ball soup.
They do great wine! For €30 we got a bottle of Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc. Also got slices of Pumpkin Pie, which was really good.

For a late night feast, this is 100% the place to go.

originalText.text: Love the split pea soup and have been a long time customer at Chelsea Square. Today 1/14/24 , ordered some take out food and now I know what is that special seasoning, (Roach droppings). I was waiting for my food and saw a good size roach crawling on the frother machine. I mention to worker and manager, and let's hope they get an exterminator. Then, I ordered a cheese burger and who makes a cheese burger with no lettuce or tomato. Just cheese...

originalText.text: The service was kinda slow and the prices are steep for a dinner. It’s nice though that it’s 24 hours. I got the veggie burger deluxe which was $18. It was a decent burger. My friends got ice cream and a fruit salad and they thought that was pretty good. It looked like they had a bunch of pies and cakes out so those might be worth the visit.

originalText.text: The Chelsea Square Restaurant in New York is a hidden gem that captures the essence of a cozy, old-fashioned diner. With its nostalgic ambiance, hearty and delicious breakfast offerings, and top-notch service, it is a must-visit for those seeking a taste of the past in the bustling heart of Manhattan. Whether you're a local looking for a comforting breakfast or a visitor in search of a genuine diner experience, this place won't disappoint. My visit left me with fond memories, and I look forward to returning to relive the nostalgia and indulge in more delightful breakfasts in the future.
